Paring an earlier decline, futures for the Dow Jones Industrial Average  fell 4 points to 13,026, while those for the Standard & Poor's 500 index  fell 2 points to 1,404.80. The disability and life insurer has seen its core earnings mostly decline over the past five quarters, offsetting slight increases in premiums from its U.S. business. Headlines.Headline: Unum Group 3Q Net Falls 6.9% On Investments, Core Profit Rises

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Unum Group's UNM third-quarter earnings fell 6.9% because of investment losses, but the disability and life insurer's core earnings were up as strength in its main U.S. business overshadowed deterioration in its smaller units. The latest period had net realized after-tax investment losses of $15.9 million, versus slim investment gains in the year earlier period. Earnings in the U.S. business, Unum's biggest, were up 7.2% on a premium income increase of 1.3%. Profitability, however, in its smaller units weakened, echoing the performance of the first quarter after a strong showing in the second.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Unum 3Q Profit Inches Down On Year-Earlier Gain; Rev Grows

PARAGRAPH.#text: Unum Group's UNM third-quarter earnings inched down on a small year-earlier investment gain, as the disability and life insurer also reported modest revenue growth. President and Chief Executive Thomas R. Watjen said while the environment remains challenging, the third-quarter results met expectations as positive results in Unum's U.S. and Colonial Life operations offset lower profit from the U.K. The company, which also runs employee-benefits programs, skirted the worst investment losses that hobbled some other insurers in the financial crisis because it wasn't exposed to subprime securities.

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Employers - long the provider of pensions and retirement plans - have begun to assist workers with college savings. Many are helping employees save more systematically with payroll deductions to their 529 college savings accounts. A small but growing number of businesses are contributing directly to workers' 529 accounts in the same way as they have matched 401(k) contributions. The trend is expected to increase significantly, especially after the recession ends. Much depends on what happens in Illinois, which in August became the first state to offer a tax credit when the employer matches the employee's contributions to the Illinois 529 plan.

Headlines.Author: Victoria E. Knight
Headlines.Headline: GETTING PERSONAL: Financial Medicine For A Health Disaster

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Tuesday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Finding the gaps in health and disability coverage, and then filling them, may be one of the best ways to protect against financial disaster. The costs of illness contributed to six out of 10 personal bankruptcies filed by Americans in 2007, according to a study published online by the American Journal of Medicine. Three quarters of those affected had health insurance. "It's perilous to assume that we are protected just because we have a health insurance card in our wallet," says Karen Pollitz, a research professor at Georgetown University's Health Policy Institute.

The statement sparked worries over economic growth. Elsewhere, the German police were questioning three men on suspicion of planning terrorist attacks in Germany, the BBC reported on its Web site. U.S. retailers were offering mixed results, with some weak same-store sales for January emerging.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: MSN, Yahoo top international Web sites

#text:
U.S.-based Web companies' Internet sites dominated the first international
    Internet audience information report from Nielsen/NetRatings

. In Australia,
    Ireland, Singapore and the United Kingdom,
and

were the top domains for audience, with MSN.com
    also number one in New Zealand, followed by the domestic

.
    "Both MSN and Yahoo have risen to the top by carefully developing relationships with
    local content providers in those markets," said NetRatings analytical services vice
    president Allen Weiner. Reporting on usage patterns of the 95,000 users participating in
    its research panel, the firm said Web surfers in Australia and New Zealand are online an
    average of nearly eight hours monthly. "This is likely due to those countries'
    efforts to institute decentralization, which leads to competition, driving phone prices
    down and overall usage up," said Weiner. By contrast, he pointed out, even with a
    number of ISPs offering free access in the United Kingdom, "overall home usage is low
    compared to the U.S. Having to pay for local phone charges discourages very heavy
    usage," he said.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: MSN, Yahoo top international Web sites

Headlines.Headline: Palladium rebounds to finish higher - 04-23-98

#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW)
    -- June
    palladium
rebounded late in the session, slightly rising past the price of gold

.
    Volume in the palladium market is light as the Russian State Duma votes again Friday on
    Sergei Kiriyenko's nomination as prime minister. Kiriyenko was nominated by Russian
    President Boris Yeltsin after Yeltsin fired his entire cabinet in March. Analysts warn
    that if the Duma votes down Kiriyenko for a third time, the delay in metals exports may
    extend into the third quarter of the year.
    Palladium rose the extended daily limit, $12.00 in early trade, then plunged the down-side
    limit amid reports Kiriyenko is gaining support.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Palladium rebounds to finish higher - 04-23-98

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: New investors overly optimistic?

#text:
As speculators continue to push a Dow 10,000, mutual fund
    investors are pouring more and more cash into stock funds. The

reports that $24.2 billion was invested in stock funds in February, a
    65 percent increase from the January total. Assets for the whole fund industry, including
    stock, bond, municipal, and money market funds stand at $4.8 trillion. As popularity
    in funds and investor optimism flourish, anxious mutual fund industry executives wonder
    how to alert their shareholders to a bear market potential. The problem is that millions
    of neophyte investors jumped into funds in the last year or so. Surveys indicate that many
    think double-digit total returns are the norm, that funds are insured by the government,
    and that stocks rarely go down very much.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: New investors overly optimistic?

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Times-Mirror drives past Q1 views - 04-23-98

#text: Times-Mirror (TMC)

shares could rise Friday after the newspaper publisher reported first-quarter net income
    of 44 cents a share, two cents ahead of Wall Street estimates. Revenue rose 4 percent to
    $803.9 million from $773.8 million in the year-ago period. A 26 percent jump in newsprint
    expenses led to a 5 percent decline in operating profit in the Newspaper Publishing
    segment, but advertising revenue rose 6 percent to $415.6 million from the year-ago total
    of $391.2 million.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Times-Mirror drives past Q1 views - 04-23-98

Headlines.Headline: Broadcom profits soar 4/22/98

#text: Newly public Broadcom Corp. (BRCM)

,
    already one of the week's high fliers, is prepared for another liftoff Thursday after
    reporting a big increase in first-quarter income. The chip design company earned 19 cents
    a share, compared to a loss of 3 cents a year ago. Sales skyrocketed to $35.3 million from
    $5 million in the same period last year. Shares closed unchanged at 55 1/4, more than
    double the stock's $24 offering price on Friday.
